  • ⭐The stuff which the most of this note is about

Volume stimuli override osmotic stimuli in the control of vasopressin secretion

  • Cirrhosis -> vasodilation -> lower pressure sensed

ADH secretion stimulation in both conditions --> hyponatremia

Both ADH release and the associated reduction in the serum sodium concentration parallel the severity of the heart failure or cirrhosis.

Diabetes insipidus presenting features:

  • Polyuria, polydypsia and nocturia.

  • Labs:

    • low Urinary specific gravity of < 1.005
    • low Urinary osmolality < 200 mOsm/Kg
    • high plasma osmolality (random p.osmolality > 287)
    • Plasma Na is in the high normal range.
      • Usually severe hypernatremia is usually not present
        • intact thirst stimulation and drinking will provide water replacement.

  • the most common from is central DI

    • First diagnose DI using the water deprivation test: monitor urine osmolality with water deprivation.
      • In healthy individuals, water deprivation leads to a urinary osmolality that is 2-4 times greater than plasma osmolality.
      • In healthy people, administration of ADH causes a rise of urine osmolality of less than 9%.
      • In Central and peripheral DI, UO will be < 300 mOsm/Kg after water deprivation AND in central DI, administration of ADH will cause urine osmolality to rise to > 750 mOsm/Kg.

  • Commonest cause of SIADH is antidepressants and antipsychotics.

  • Thyroid functions and cortisols MUST be normal to diagnose SIADH.

[!TIP] Mnemonic

  • Cushing's disease: Pituitary hypersecretion of ACTH
  • Cushing's syndrome: Manifestation of hypercortisolism

Males had a three times greater incidence of the ectopic ACTH syndrome 30 years ago, but the increasing incidence of lung cancer in cigarette-smoking females has narrowed that margin
Commonest cause of Cushing's syndrome is iatrogenic;

  • All glucocorticoids suppress ACTH -> ACTH, and serum cortisol will be low in iatrogenic cushing's syndrome.

The diagnosis of Cushing syndrome is established when at least two different first-line tests are unequivocally abnormal, and physiologic hypercortisolism has been excluded
[!INFO] TLDR;
3 confirmatory tests for confirm hypercortisolism

  1. BTSC
  2. 24-UFC
  3. LD-DST

3 localization tests once hypercortisolism is confirmed

  1. HD-DST
  2. CRH-ST
  3. Desmopressin-ST
  • One of these is done; if positive, it confirms pituitary source of ACTH. If negative, it confirms ectopic ACTH.
  • If cortisol is found to be elevated with the above preliminary tests, next step is to exclude physiologic hypercortisolism.
  • AKA - pseudo Cushing syndrome.
  • Clinically, these patients usually do not have skin or muscle manifestations of Cushing Syndrome.
  1. Severe major depression
    1. insulin tolerance test can be used to differentiate this.
    2. Insulin induced hypoglycaemia will cause a normal rise in cortisol in a depressed patient but no rise in true cushing's syndrome.
  2. Poorly controlled DM
  3. OSA
  4. Malnutrition

[!INFO] These tests are called "Localisation tests".

  • First line test for this is measuring ACTH levels.
  • Do 9am and midnight plasma ACTH.
  • Because of cyclical variations, testing at two different times is recommended.
  • ACTH < 5pg/ML = ACTH independent hypercortisolism
  • ACTH > 20pg/mL = ACTH dependent hypercortisolism.
    1. Corticotroph pituitary tumours respond to CRH (despite being tumours).
      1. A rise in cortisol with CRH stimulation confirms a pituitary source of ACTH.
  1. High dose dexamethasone suppression test
    1. Corticotroph tumours retain sensitivity to negative FB by glucocorticoids
  2. Desmopressin stimulation test
    1. Used clinically when CRH is not available
    2. ADH stimulates ACTH release.
    3. Desmopressin is used to mimic this effect. (ADH and desmopressin have a similar action to CRH)

[!INFO] Sources of ectopic ACTH

Ectopic adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH) syndrome accounts for 10%–20% of the cases of ACTH-dependent Cushing's syndrome (1). Ectopic ACTH secretion typically results from an occult, slow-growing bronchial carcinoid tumor. Source

  • Murmur increases with inspiration. (Carvallo sign)

[!INFO] Clinical features of IE

  • Isolated Splenomegaly (not hepatosplenomegaly) is a feature of IE.
    • esp. in chronic I.E. Probably due to prolonged immune stimulation. Source
  • Clubbing is a feature (but only 10% have it) (box 30.46 K&C)
  • IE can be acute or sub acute in presentation.

Brain tumours

[!INFO] "blastoma" means arising from precursor cells

  • Adult tumours usually arise above the tentorium
  • Children get tumours below the tentorium
  • Commonest brain tumours in adult are due to metz.
  • Commonest primary tumours are glioblastomas.
    • Poor prognosis.
    • Solid tumours with central necrosis.
    • Ring enhancement on contrast CT.
    • Histology: Pleomorphic tumour cells.
    • Cause vasogenic oedema (which is treated with Dexamathasone)
  • Second commonest adult primary tumour:
    • [[2017-GM-OCT#meningioma]]
    • bening

Other brain tumours:

Tumour features
Vestibular schwanoma Bening; causes deafness and facial palsy
Hemangiobalstoma Associated with VHL, benign
Ependymoma Occurs in 4th ventricle
  • commonest paediatric tumour is pilocytic astrocytoma. Good prognosis.
  • Craniopharyngima: Commonest paediatric supratentorial tumour.

Renal stones - urolithiasis

  • Calcium oxalate are the commonest.
  • Struvite - tripple phosphate (Calcium, magnesium and ammonium phosphate)
    • Forms in alkaline urine associated with UTI.
    • Commoner in women.
    • They form staghorn calculi.
  • Uric acid stone:
    • Forms in acidic urine; associated with high protein diet.
  • Cystine stones:
    • cystinuria; genetic defect; stones occur in young people. (NOT THE SAME as homocystinuria)
  • uric acid and xantine (under 'other') are radioluscent.
